        public static float manhattanDistanceBetween(Vec3f v1,
                                             Vec3f v2)
        Calculate and return the Manhattan distance between two Vec3f objects.

        The Manhattan distance is an approximate distance between two points, but can be calculated faster than the exact distance.

        Further reading: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/floataxicab_geometry http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3693514/very-fast-3d-distance-check

        Parameters:
        v1 - The first point.
        v2 - The second point.
        Returns:
        The Manhattan distance between the two points.

      • genPerpendicularVectorQuick

        public static Vec3f genPerpendicularVectorQuick(Vec3f u)
        Return a normalised Vec3f which is perpendicular to the vector provided.

        This is a very fast method of generating a perpendicular vector that works for any vector which is 5 degrees or more from vertical 'up'.

        The code in this method is adapted from: http://blog.selfshadow.com/2011/10/17/perp-vectors/

        Parameters:
        u - The vector to use as the basis for generating the perpendicular vector.
        Returns:
        A normalised vector which is perpendicular to the provided vector argument.

      • genPerpendicularVectorHM

        public static Vec3f genPerpendicularVectorHM(Vec3f u)
        Method to generate a vector perpendicular to another one using the Hughes-Muller method.

        The returned vector is normalised.

        The code in this method is adapted from: http://blog.selfshadow.com/2011/10/17/perp-vectors/

        Further reading: Hughes, J. F., Muller, T., "Building an Orthonormal Basis from a Unit Vector", Journal of Graphics Tools 4:4 (1999), 33-35.

        Parameters:
        u - The vector with regard to which we will generate a perpendicular unit vector.
        Returns:
        A normalised vector which is perpendicular to the provided vector argument.

        The returned vector is normalised.

      • getAngleBetweenRads

        public static float getAngleBetweenRads(Vec3f v1,
                                        Vec3f v2)
        Calculate and return the angle between two vectors in radians.

        The result will always be a positive value between zero and pi (3.14159f) radians.

        This method does not modify the provided vectors, but does use normalised versions of them in the calculations.

        Parameters:
        v1 - The first vector.
        v2 - The second vector.
        Returns:
        The angle between the vector in radians.

      • getAngleBetweenDegs

        public static float getAngleBetweenDegs(Vec3f v1,
                                        Vec3f v2)
        Calculate and return the angle between two vectors in degrees.

        The result will always be a positive value between [0..180) degrees.

        This method does not modify the provided vectors, but does use normalised versions of them in the calculations.

        Parameters:
        v1 - The first vector.
        v2 - The second vector.
        Returns:
        The angle between the vector in degrees.

      • getSignedAngleBetweenDegs

        public static float getSignedAngleBetweenDegs(Vec3f referenceVector,
                                              Vec3f otherVector,
                                              Vec3f normalVector)
        Return a signed angle between two vectors within the range -179.9f..180.0f degrees.
        Parameters:
        referenceVector - The baseline vector which we consider to be at zero degrees.
        otherVector - The vector we will use to calculate the signed angle with respect to the reference vector.
        normalVector - The normal vector (i.e. vector perpendicular to) both the reference and 'other' vectors.
        Returns:
        The signed angle from the reference vector to the other vector in degrees.

      • getAngleLimitedUnitVectorDegs

        public static Vec3f getAngleLimitedUnitVectorDegs(Vec3f vecToLimit,
                                                  Vec3f vecBaseline,
                                                  float angleLimitDegs)
        Return an angle limited vector with regard to another vector.

        Parameters:
        vecToLimit - The vector which we will limit to a given angle with regard to the the baseline vector.
        vecBaseline - The vector which will be used as the baseline / frame-of-reference when rotating the vecToLimit.
        angleLimitDegs - The maximum angle which the vecToLimit may be rotated away from the vecBaseline, in degrees.
        Returns:
        The rotated vecToLimit, which is constraint to a maximum of the angleLimitDegs argument.

        public static void add(Vec3f source,
                       Vec3f other)

        This method does not perform any memory allocations - it merely adds 'other' to 'source'.

        Parameters:

        other - The vector we will add to the 'source' vector.

      • divideBy

        public Vec3f divideBy(float value)
        Return a vector which is the result of component-wise division of by the given scalar value. This vector remains unchanged.

        Attempting to divide by zero will, unsurprisingly, throw a DivideByZero exception.

        Parameters:
        value - The value to divide each component of this vector by.
        Returns:
        A vector which is the result of dividing each component of this vector by the provided argument.

      • projectOntoPlane

        public Vec3f projectOntoPlane(Vec3f planeNormal)
        Return a vector which is the result of projecting this vector onto a plane described by the provided surface normal.

        Neither the vector on which this method is called or the provided plane normal vector are modified.

        If the plane surface normal has a magnitude of zero then an IllegalArgumentException is thrown.

        Parameters:
        planeNormal - The normal that describes the plane onto which we will project this vector.
        Returns:
        A projected version of this vector.

      • getDirectionUV

        public static Vec3f getDirectionUV(Vec3f v1,
                                   Vec3f v2)
        Calculate and return the direction unit vector from point a to point b.

        If the opposite direction is required then the argument order can be swapped or the the result can simply be negated.

        Parameters:
        v1 - The first location.
        v2 - The second location.
        Returns:
        The normalised direction unit vector between point v1 and point v2.

      • randomise

        public void randomise(float min,
                      float max)
        Randomise the components of this vector to be random values between the provided half-open range as described by the minimum and maximum value arguments.
        Parameters:
        min - The minimum value for any given component (inclusive).
        max - The maximum value for any given component (exclusive, i.e. a max of 5.0f will be assigned values up to 4.9999f or such).
